# Coding Standards

- Functional Components only.
- Use Hooks.
- Use TypeScript-ready architecture (even if JavaScript is used initially).
- Small reusable components.
- Avoid duplicate code.
- Keep components under 250 lines where possible.
- Separate UI from business logic.
- Use clean naming conventions.
- Use lazy loading for pages.
- Use absolute imports if configured.

---

# Development Rules

- Build frontend before backend.
- Every page should be responsive.
- Every page should use mock data.
- Every page should have loading states.
- Every page should have empty states.
- Every page should have error states.
- Forms should include validation.
- Components should be reusable.
- Code should be production-ready.

---

# Future Backend

Backend will be developed after frontend approval.

Backend will provide

- REST APIs
- JWT Authentication
- MongoDB Database
- File Upload
- Notifications
- Email Service
- Role Management
- Activity Logs

Do NOT generate backend code until frontend has been approved.

---

# AI Development Instructions

When generating code:

- Follow React best practices.
- Prioritize reusable components.
- Write clean, maintainable code.
- Keep UI consistent across the application.
- Avoid unnecessary complexity.
- Create modular architecture.
- Prefer composition over duplication.
- Use Tailwind CSS utilities effectively.
- Ensure accessibility where practical.
- Generate production-quality code suitable for scaling.

The objective is to build a premium-quality home management application that is elegant, fast, and easy to maintain.